// Auto-generated trading glossary (educational, non-sensitive).
export const GLOSSARY=[{"group":"Tape & trend","term":"Regime","what":"A one-word label KOBE assigns to each market's current behavior: trending_up, trending_down, ranging, squeeze, volatile_chop, or mixed.","why":"Each regime turns a different playbook on or off, so the wrong tactic in the wrong regime is the fastest way to bleed money.","example":"BTC tagged trending_up enables breakout entries, while a volatile_chop tag shuts them off entirely."},{"group":"Tape & trend","term":"Regime confidence (conf)","what":"A 0-to-1 score showing how strongly the data agrees with the regime label.","why":"A confident read justifies acting; a shaky read (conflicting signals) means stand down or size smaller.","example":"trending_up at conf 0.83 clears the bar to trade, while a mixed read at conf 0.41 gets skipped."},{"group":"Tape & trend","term":"ADX","what":"A 0-100 gauge of how strongly price is moving in one direction, regardless of which direction.","why":"It separates markets worth riding from markets that just wiggle: ADX at or above 22 means a real trend, below 20 means chop.","example":"NVDA with ADX 28 qualifies for trend-following rules; at ADX 14 the same chart would be treated as chop."},{"group":"Tape & trend","term":"EMA20 / EMA50","what":"Smoothed average prices over roughly the last 20 and 50 days, weighting recent days more.","why":"They define the trend's spine: price holding above EMA50 ('above water') keeps a name eligible for longs.","example":"IRDM at $31.20 versus its EMA50 of $28.90 is above water and stays on the buy list."},{"group":"Tape & trend","term":"Extension (ext)","what":"How far price has stretched away from its EMA20, measured in units of typical daily movement (ATR).","why":"Buying something already stretched means a bad entry price and a wide stop, so high extension blocks chasing.","example":"A stock sitting +2.6 ATRs above EMA20 is too extended to enter; KOBE waits for it to pull back toward the average."},{"group":"Tape & trend","term":"ATR / ATR%","what":"Average True Range is how many dollars an asset typically moves in a day; ATR% expresses that as a percent of price.","why":"It is the yardstick for everything else: stop distances, extension, and position size all scale off ATR so a wild asset and a calm one get treated fairly.","example":"BTC with a $2,100 ATR on a $67,500 price has an ATR% of about 3.1%, so a 1.7x ATR stop sits roughly $3,600 away."},{"group":"Tape & trend","term":"Relative Strength (RS)","what":"A score comparing an asset's last 3 months of performance against a benchmark like the S&P 500.","why":"Money flows to leaders, so KOBE prefers buying what is already beating the market rather than bargain-hunting laggards.","example":"IRDM showing RS +72.8 has crushed the benchmark over 3 months and ranks near the top of the candidate list."},{"group":"Tape & trend","term":"Donchian channel / breakout","what":"A band drawn at the highest high and lowest low of the past N days; a breakout is a close beyond that band.","why":"A close above every price of the last N days is objective evidence of new buying pressure, with no interpretation required.","example":"BTC closing at $66,900, above its 20-day Donchian high of $66,400, fires a breakout entry signal."},{"group":"Tape & trend","term":"RSI(2)","what":"An ultra-fast 2-day momentum gauge that drops near zero after a couple of sharp down days.","why":"In an established uptrend, a very low RSI(2) marks a short-term panic dip — a buy-the-pullback trigger rather than a warning.","example":"IRDM, still above its EMA50, prints RSI(2) of 4 after a two-day dip, triggering a mean-reversion buy."},{"group":"Tape & trend","term":"Bollinger bandwidth percentile / squeeze","what":"A measure of how compressed price movement is right now compared with the past year, where a very low percentile is called a squeeze.","why":"Quiet periods store energy: big moves tend to launch from squeezes, so KOBE watches them for the breakout that follows.","example":"A stock whose bandwidth sits in the 8th percentile of the past year is flagged as a squeeze candidate ahead of its next big move."},{"group":"Risk & sizing","term":"Risk per trade (0.75% / 1% cap)","what":"The maximum planned loss on any single trade: 0.75% of account equity by default, with 1% as an unbreakable ceiling.","why":"Capping each loss to a sliver of the account means even a long losing streak is survivable and recoverable.","example":"On $40,000 of equity, a new trade is built to lose at most $300, and the system rejects anything that could lose more than $400."},{"group":"Risk & sizing","term":"Hard stop (tighten-only)","what":"A pre-set exit price placed at entry that closes the trade automatically, and that may only ever move closer to current price, never farther away.","why":"It converts 'I hope it comes back' into a fixed, known maximum loss that no emotion can widen mid-trade.","example":"A BTC long from $67,500 carries a hard stop at $63,900; it can later rise to $65,200 but can never be loosened back down."},{"group":"Risk & sizing","term":"Trailing stop (chandelier)","what":"A stop that hangs a fixed number of ATRs below the highest price reached since entry, ratcheting up as the trade works.","why":"It lets winners run while steadily locking in gains, so a good trade cannot round-trip back to a loss.","example":"Trailing 3 ATRs under BTC's highest close, the stop ratchets from $63,900 to $66,800 as the rally extends."},{"group":"Risk & sizing","term":"Position sizing","what":"Quantity is computed as the dollar risk budget divided by the distance between entry and stop.","why":"Size comes from math, not conviction, so a wide-stop trade is automatically small and a tight-stop trade can be larger at the same dollar risk.","example":"A $300 risk budget on BTC with a $3,600 gap from entry to the $63,900 stop yields a 0.083 BTC position."},{"group":"Risk & sizing","term":"Notional caps (40% / 30% crypto)","what":"A ceiling on the total dollar value of any single position: 40% of equity for stocks, 30% for crypto.","why":"Stops protect against normal moves, but caps protect against gaps and overnight shocks where a stop can be jumped.","example":"On a $40,000 account, no stock position may exceed $16,000 and no crypto position may exceed $12,000, regardless of how good the setup looks."},{"group":"Risk & sizing","term":"Correlation buckets","what":"Assets that tend to move together are grouped into buckets, and combined exposure per bucket is capped.","why":"Three positions that all fall together are really one big bet, so bucketing stops a single theme from sinking the whole book.","example":"BTC and ETH share the crypto bucket, so KOBE refuses to hold full-size positions in both at once."},{"group":"Risk & sizing","term":"Drawdown / high-water mark","what":"The high-water mark is the account's all-time peak equity, and drawdown is the percentage you currently sit below it.","why":"Drawdown is the truest measure of pain and risk-taking, and it drives the system's automatic defensive responses.","example":"Equity that peaked at $42,000 and now reads $39,900 is in a 5% drawdown from its high-water mark."},{"group":"Risk & sizing","term":"Drawdown ladder","what":"A preset schedule that automatically cuts risk per trade as drawdown deepens.","why":"It forces the system to trade smaller exactly when most humans tilt and trade bigger to 'win it back.'","example":"At a 5% drawdown the risk budget steps down from 0.75% to 0.50% of equity, and it steps down again at 10%."},{"group":"Risk & sizing","term":"Daily & weekly loss caps; cooldowns","what":"Hard limits on how much can be lost in a single day or week before new trading halts, plus a waiting period before re-entering a symbol that just stopped out.","why":"Losses cluster, and these circuit breakers prevent one bad morning from snowballing into a catastrophic week.","example":"Down 2% by midday trips the daily cap and blocks new entries until tomorrow, while a stopped-out symbol sits in a multi-day cooldown."},{"group":"System decisions","term":"Quality score","what":"A 0-to-1 grade for each candidate trade, blending signal strength (40%), regime fit (25%), recent strategy performance (20%), and trading cost (15%), with 0.55 required to pass.","why":"It forces every trade to clear one objective bar, so only the best few setups each day get capital.","example":"A setup scoring 0.61 goes through to sizing, while a 0.52 is skipped at the 0.55 gate even though its chart looks tempting."},{"group":"System decisions","term":"Thesis","what":"A short written statement, recorded before entry, of why the trade should work, where the stop is, and what would prove it wrong.","why":"Writing the reason down up front prevents the story from being rewritten mid-trade to justify holding a loser.","example":"'IRDM Donchian breakout, RS +72.8, stop $27.40, invalid on a close below EMA50' is logged before the order is placed."},{"group":"System decisions","term":"Risk verdict (approved / vetoed)","what":"An independent risk check that runs after a trade idea is generated and returns either approved or vetoed.","why":"Separating the idea-generator from the risk-approver means no single component can talk itself into a rule-breaking trade.","example":"A proposed ETH entry is vetoed because adding it would push the crypto correlation bucket past its cap."},{"group":"System decisions","term":"Posture (reduce-only)","what":"A system-level stance, written to a file by the supervising model, that can restrict the account to reduce-only — exits allowed, no new buying.","why":"It gives the system a way to de-risk the whole book at once when conditions deteriorate, without flattening everything.","example":"After three consecutive losses the posture file flips to reduce-only, so KOBE can close BTC but cannot open new positions."},{"group":"System decisions","term":"Pass day","what":"A day on which the system deliberately takes no new trades because nothing met its standards.","why":"Doing nothing is a position too — most edge comes from a handful of good days, and forcing trades on the other days just pays fees.","example":"No candidate clears the 0.55 quality gate on Tuesday, so KOBE logs a pass day and sits in cash."},{"group":"System decisions","term":"Kill switch & 3-gate arm","what":"The kill switch instantly halts all trading activity, and resuming live trading requires three separate, deliberate confirmations (the 3-gate arm).","why":"Stopping should take one click and restarting should take effort, so panic exits are easy and careless re-entries are hard.","example":"After hitting the kill switch during a flash crash, the operator must flip all three arm gates before KOBE will place another live order."},{"group":"System decisions","term":"Cost guard","what":"A rule rejecting any trade whose expected profit is less than twice the full round-trip cost of fees, spread, and slippage.","why":"Small edges get eaten alive by costs, so this filter weeds out trades that only look profitable before expenses.","example":"A setup expecting $48 of edge against a $30 round-trip cost is rejected because the edge must be at least $60."},{"group":"System decisions","term":"Paper vs live mode","what":"Paper mode runs the full system with simulated fills and fake money; live mode places real orders with real capital.","why":"Paper is where strategy and pipeline bugs get exposed cheaply, so nothing graduates to live until it has proven itself there.","example":"The breakout strategy must show positive results across weeks of paper trading before the 3-gate arm switches it to live."},{"group":"Performance","term":"R-multiple","what":"Trade results measured in units of the original planned risk, so a trade that risked $300 and made $840 is +2.8R.","why":"It normalizes every trade to the same risk yardstick: a disciplined system's losses land near -1R while trailed winners stretch to +2R, +3R and beyond.","example":"A month of -1R, -1R, +0.4R, +2.8R nets +1.2R overall — profitable despite losing most trades."},{"group":"Performance","term":"Win rate vs expectancy","what":"Win rate is the percentage of trades that make money, while expectancy is the average amount earned (in R or dollars) per trade across wins and losses.","why":"A high win rate with tiny wins and huge losses still goes broke — expectancy, not win rate, is what actually compounds the account.","example":"A 38% win rate with +2.5R average winners against -1R losers yields a healthy expectancy of about +0.33R per trade."},{"group":"Performance","term":"Profit factor","what":"Total gross profits divided by total gross losses over a period.","why":"It is a one-number health check: above 1.0 the system makes money, and around 1.5 or better it has a comfortable margin over costs and bad luck.","example":"$9,200 of gross wins against $5,400 of gross losses gives a profit factor of 1.7."}];
